Hong Kong Stocks Fluctuate as Oil Companies Gain; Tencent Fall

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-04-07T02:38:33Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-07/hong-kong-stocks-fluctuate-as-oil-companies-gain-tencent-fall.html
Hong Kong stocks fell for the first
day in six as carmakers dropped after  China ’s government raised
retail prices for gasoline and diesel. Internet company  Tencent
Holdings Ltd. (700)  sank after it chief executive sold shares.  Guangzhou Automobile Group Co. slid 2.2 percent, while
Geely Automobile Holdings Ltd., the unit of the Chinese
automaker that owns Volvo Cars, declined 2.3 percent. Tencent
Holdings, China’s biggest Internet company, slid 1.2 percent
after its chief executive officer Ma Huateng disposed of 2
million shares.  The Hang Seng Index fell 0.3 percent to 24,203.78 as of
9:45 a.m. local time, after gaining as much as 0.3 percent.
About three stocks fell for each that rose on the 45-member
gauge. The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index of Chinese
companies’ H-shares dropped 0.5 percent to 13,588.02.  Futures on the  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  declined 0.3 percent to
24,217.  To contact the reporter on this story:
